        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix: add configurable SQLite mmap disable for NFS-backed storage",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n- Adds `OPENCLAW_SQLITE_MMAP=0` env var and `storage.sqliteMmap: false` config option to disable SQLite memory-mapped I/O\n- Default behaviour is unchanged (mmap enabled)\n- Applied to all 4 SQLite connection sites: task registry, flow registry, memory sync store, QMD manager\n\n## Problem\n\nWhen openclaw's state directory lives on an NFS mount (common in Kubernetes with NFS provisioners like `nfs-subdir-external-provisioner`), SQLite's WAL mode shared-memory (`-shm`) files use mmap which NFS does not support reliably. A transient server interruption causes the kernel to deliver **SIGBUS (exit code 135)**, crashing the gateway process.\n\nWe observed this in production on a Raspberry Pi k3s cluster with NFS-backed PVCs — the openclaw pod would crash every ~15 hours with exit code 135 and no application-level error in the logs.\n\n## Fix\n\nA new helper `applySqliteMmapPragma()` conditionally applies `PRAGMA mmap_size = 0` at connection open time. Resolution order:\n\n1. `OPENCLAW_SQLITE_MMAP` env var (`0`/`false` to disable, `1`/`true` to enable)\n2. `storage.sqliteMmap` in openclaw.json\n3. Default: `true` (preserves existing behaviour)\n\nThe env var is convenient for Kubernetes where you can set it in the pod spec without touching config:\n\n```yaml\nenv:\n  - name: OPENCLAW_SQLITE_MMAP\n    value: \"0\"\n```\n\nOr in openclaw.json:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"storage\": {\n    \"sqliteMmap\": false\n  }\n}\n```\n\n## Performance impact\n\nNegligible for the small databases openclaw uses. `PRAGMA mmap_size = 0` falls back to regular `read()` syscalls — the same I/O path SQLite used before mmap was introduced.",
